Loans data: first look

Dzianis Sokalau

6/25/2017

Loan is cool thing for both lender and borrower. For lender it is tool for making money. For borrower it is opportynity to have things (business, having a home or car, education)

The issue is that some loans are going to be paid and some arent
and challenge is find how to predict future status of a loan

This script is for take first look to the loans data

The data is from https://www.kaggle.com/wendykan/lending-club-loan-data
Original source is Lending Club: https://www.lendingclub.com/info/download-data.action

Lets take a look what variables are in the data

we have already stored data into df

There are a lot of information in the table. Since in the current script we want just make first exploration, we will consider some of them:
loan_status - current status of the loan
loan_amnt - the listed amount of the loan applied for by the borrower. If at some point in time, the credit department reduces the loan amount, then it will be reflected in this value
purpose - A category provided by the borrower for the loan request
annual_inc - the self-reported annual income provided by the borrower during registration
dti - a ratio calculated using the borrower???s total monthly debt payments on the total debt obligations, excluding mortgage and the requested LC loan, divided by the borrower???s self-reported monthly income
int_rate - interest Rate on the loan

What are the loans statuses and what the frequency of each status

l_status <- df %>% 
                group_by(loan_status) %>% 
                summarise(count = n() / 1000) %>%
                arrange(desc(count))

In this case we should compare only closed loans or already more likely to be bad loans Bad loans are Default, Charged Off and Late (31-120 days) Good loans are those were fully paid - Fully Paid

b_loans <- c("Charged Off", 
              "Late (31-120 days)",
              "Default")
g_loans <- "Fully Paid"
l_status <- l_status[l_status$loan_status %in% c(unlist(b_loans), g_loans),]
l_status <- transform(l_status, 
                      loan_status = reorder(loan_status, desc(count)))

And what we have now is on the chart bellow

ggplot(l_status, aes(x=loan_status, y=count)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title="Number of Loans by Status", x = "Loan Status", y = "Loans count, k") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1.5, linetype="dashed", color = "red", size = 0.5) + 
  theme_minimal()

The red dashed line on the chart separates good from bad loans

According to the data share of bad loans is around 22%

sum(l_status[l_status$loan_status %in% b_loans, 'count'])/
  sum(l_status[l_status$loan_status %in% c(unlist(b_loans), g_loans), 'count'])
## [1] 0.218443

Now we should remain only closed loans in the table. In addition we will create new variable result with 0 for bad loans and 1 for good loans. It will help us in the future to calculate probability for loan to be paid depends on different factors

df <- df[df$loan_status %in% c(unlist(b_loans), g_loans),]
df$result <- 1
df[df$loan_status %in% b_loans, 'result'] <- 0

Some factors on loans status

Just as an example lets take a look on what factors may impact on loans quality
bellow we consider such variables like loan amount, annual income of borrower, dti and interst rate

df %>% 
  group_by(loan_status) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), 
            med_amount = median(loan_amnt),
            med_inc = median(annual_inc),
            med_dti = median(dti), 
            med_int = median(int_rate)) %>%
  arrange(desc(count))
## # A tibble: 4 x 6
##          loan_status  count med_amount med_inc med_dti med_int
##                <chr>  <int>      <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1         Fully Paid 207723      12000   64162   15.75   13.11
## 2        Charged Off  45248      12675   56000   18.35   15.80
## 3 Late (31-120 days)  11591      14000   60000   19.57   15.61
## 4            Default   1219      13675   56000   19.84   15.99

Lets translate this numbers into visualization

ggplot(df, aes(loan_status, loan_amnt, fill = as.factor(loan_status))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title="Loan Amount vs Loan Status", x="Status", y="Amount") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

And nothing special here, amount for fully paid loans a little bit lower than for others

The similar thing is for borrower income:
it is a little bit higher for thouse who paid loan successfully

ggplot(df, aes(loan_status, annual_inc, fill = as.factor(loan_status))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(df$annual_inc, c(0.1, 0.9), na.rm = T)) +
  labs(title="Annual Income vs Loan Status", x="Status", y="Annual Income") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

The last thing Im going to consider today is interest rate. It depends on grade and subgrade of borrower: the more risky borrower the higher inters rate
on the other hand. Interesting thing is the higher interest rate the more complicated to pay loan

ggplot(df, aes(loan_status, int_rate, fill = as.factor(loan_status))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(df$int_rate, c(0.1, 0.9))) +
  labs(title="Interest Rate vs Loan Status", x="Status", y="Interest Rate") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
